Yes—and it only sounds “cosmic” because the scale has outgrown the old vocabulary.

If we strip the mystique and keep the mechanics, what’s happening is narrative warfare at civilizational bandwidth.

⸻

1. The battlespace has shifted from territory to sense-making

Classical power fought over:
	•	land
	•	resources
	•	bodies

Modern power fights over:
	•	attention
	•	interpretation
	•	legitimacy
	•	identity coherence

When those fracture, everything else follows.

No tanks required.

⸻

2. Myth here doesn’t mean “false story” — it means meaning scaffold

In anthropology and cognitive science, myth is:
	•	a compressed explanation of “who we are”
	•	a justification for sacrifice
	•	a model of what is possible, inevitable, or forbidden

States now compete by answering:
	•	What kind of future is inevitable?
	•	Who is the hero?
	•	Who is the villain?
	•	What suffering is justified?
	•	What order is natural?

That’s myth—whether it’s wrapped in religion, progress, nationalism, technology, or morality.

⸻

3. Information ≠ data; information = direction of belief

Modern info ops don’t aim to convince everyone of one thing.

They aim to:
	•	fragment consensus
	•	overload trust
	•	exhaust discernment
	•	destabilize shared reality

If people can’t agree on:
	•	what’s real
	•	who to trust
	•	what matters

…then coordination collapses.

That’s victory without occupation.

⸻

4. Why it feels “cosmic”

Three reasons it feels larger than politics used to:

a) Global simultaneity

Billions of minds, hit at once.

b) Identity-layer targeting

Messages aren’t “policy vs policy.”
They’re:
	•	dignity vs humiliation
	•	belonging vs exile
	•	meaning vs nihilism

c) Recursive amplification

Narratives don’t just spread—they evolve, adapt, self-replicate, and weaponize feedback loops (algorithms, outrage, tribal defense).

That starts to resemble mythic struggle because it operates at the level myths always did: worldview survival.

⸻

5. Every major power is doing this (even when they deny it)

Different styles, same game:
	•	Some emphasize historical destiny
	•	Some push moral superiority
	•	Some sell technological inevitability
	•	Some trade in fear and collapse
	•	Some offer restoration myths
	•	Some offer escape myths

None are neutral.

Neutrality itself is a myth—and a fragile one.

⸻

6. The real front line: internal coherence

The states that lose aren’t the ones with weaker armies.

They’re the ones whose people:
	•	can’t tell signal from noise
	•	can’t hold contradiction
	•	can’t integrate complexity
	•	can’t separate identity from narrative attack

Once internal coherence breaks, external pressure barely matters.

⸻

7. The quiet advantage (and danger)

The most powerful actors are not those who shout the loudest—but those who can:
	•	regulate emotion
	•	slow reaction
	•	hold ambiguity
	•	preserve agency under narrative pressure

That’s why you’re noticing this now.

Seeing the game requires not being captured by it.

⸻

8. One grounded sentence to carry forward

We’re not watching nations fight over facts—we’re watching them compete to decide what kind of reality people are willing to live inside.

No mysticism required.
Just scale, speed, and human psychology.

If you want, next we can:
	•	map the dominant myth-frames in play right now
	•	break down how to recognize when you’re being targeted
	•	or talk about how individuals stay sovereign in this environment

Just say the word.